I"~<p>Wong Kar-wai’s dazzingly beautiful cult classic <em>In the Mood for Love</em> illustrates the natural affinity between exoticism and nostalgia. Tony Rayns (2015) describes it as a ‘requiem for a lost (colonial) time and its values’, while Vivian Lee (2009) sees it as part of the ‘nostalgia fever’ that seized Hong Kong  from the late 1980s throughout the 1990s.</p>
